pageTitle: "EBITDA vs SDE: Which Matters When Selling Your Business"
metaDescription: "EBITDA and SDE are both earnings metrics used in business sales, but they apply to different business sizes and produce very different valuations. Learn when each applies and how to calculate both."
canonicalPath: /guides/ebitda-vs-sde/
datePublished: "2026-01-15"
dateModified: "2026-01-15"
faqItems:
  - question: "What is the difference between EBITDA and SDE?"
    answer: "SDE adds back the owner's full compensation (salary + benefits + personal expenses), while EBITDA adds back only a market-rate management salary. SDE is higher than EBITDA for owner-operated businesses because it captures the total economic benefit to the owner. SDE is the standard for Main Street businesses under $5M revenue; EBITDA is standard for larger businesses ($5M+ revenue) managed by professional management teams."
  - question: "Is EBITDA or SDE used for restaurant valuations?"
    answer: "Most restaurant transactions under $3M in revenue use SDE multiples. Larger restaurant groups or multi-location concepts with professional management teams shift to EBITDA. The BizBuySell transaction data used by Mainstreet Benchmark covers primarily Main Street restaurant transactions and applies SDE multiples. A single-location restaurant doing $600,000 revenue with an owner-operator is an SDE business; a 5-location group doing $8M revenue with a professional GM is an EBITDA business."
  - question: "Which gives a higher valuation — EBITDA or SDE?"
    answer: "For owner-operated businesses, SDE almost always produces a higher absolute earnings number than EBITDA (because it adds back more), but EBITDA multiples are typically higher (5×–10× for mid-market businesses vs. 2×–4× for Main Street). Which produces a higher valuation depends on the specific business. The key question is which metric is appropriate for your business size and buyer type."
  - question: "When should I use EBITDA multiples instead of SDE?"
    answer: "When your business has professional management that would continue under new ownership — meaning the owner could exit without the business losing earnings. Typically this applies to businesses with revenue above $5M, SDE above $1M, or businesses where the owner is primarily a capital allocator rather than a day-to-day operator. If your business depends on you personally to generate its earnings, SDE is the appropriate metric."
