      <h1>EBITDA vs SDE: Which Matters When Selling Your Business</h1>
      <div class="guide-meta">
        <span>By {{ site.author.name }}</span>
        <span>·</span>
        <span>Updated {{ site.dataLastModified }}</span>
        <span>·</span>
        <span>8 min read</span>
      </div>
    </header>

    <section class="guide-body">

      <p>
        Business owners preparing to sell encounter two earnings metrics that look similar but produce
        very different valuations and apply to very different situations: SDE and EBITDA. Using the
        wrong one — or allowing a buyer to apply the wrong one — can result in a valuation that is
        hundreds of thousands of dollars off the mark in either direction.
      </p>

      <h2>The Definitions</h2>

      <h3>SDE — Seller's Discretionary Earnings</h3>
      <div class="formula-block">
        <p><strong>SDE = Net Profit + Owner Salary + Owner Benefits + Personal Add-Backs + Depreciation + Amortization + Interest</strong></p>
      </div>
      <p>
        SDE captures the total economic benefit a full-time owner-operator receives from the business.
        It assumes the buyer will be an individual owner-operator who replaces the seller — working in
        the business full-time and taking the same compensation structure.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is the standard metric for Main Street businesses — typically those with revenue under
        $5M or SDE under $1M. The <a href="/guides/what-is-sde/">complete SDE calculation guide</a>
        covers every add-back category in detail.
      </p>

      <h3>EBITDA — Earnings Before Interest, Taxes, Depreciation, and Amortization</h3>
      <div class="formula-block">
        <p><strong>EBITDA = Net Profit + Interest + Taxes + Depreciation + Amortization</strong></p>
      </div>
      <p>
        EBITDA normalizes earnings for financing structure (adds back interest), tax jurisdiction
        (adds back taxes), and accounting treatment (adds back D&amp;A). Unlike SDE, EBITDA does
        <em>not</em> add back the owner's full compensation — instead, it assumes a market-rate
        manager would be required to replace the owner. That replacement salary stays as an expense.
      </p>
      <p>
        EBITDA is the standard for larger businesses with professional management teams — typically
        those with revenue above $5M or EBITDA above $1M — where the buyer is a financial acquirer,
        PE firm, or strategic buyer rather than an individual owner-operator.
      </p>

      <h2>Why the Distinction Matters: A Worked Example</h2>
      <p>
        Imagine a landscaping business with $1.2M in revenue. The owner pays himself $120,000,
        takes $24,000 in health insurance through the business, expenses $12,000 in personal vehicle
        costs, and the business shows $65,000 net profit after all expenses.
      </p>

      <div class="data-table-wrap">
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th scope="col">Metric</th>
              <th scope="col">Calculation</th>
              <th scope="col">Result</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Net Profit</td>
              <td>As reported</td>
              <td>$65,000</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>EBITDA</td>
              <td>$65,000 + D&amp;A $18,000 + Interest $7,000 + Taxes $22,000</td>
              <td>$112,000</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>SDE</td>
              <td>$65,000 + Owner salary $120,000 + Benefits $24,000 + Vehicle $12,000 + D&amp;A $18,000 + Interest $7,000</td>
              <td>$246,000</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <p>
        The difference between EBITDA ($112,000) and SDE ($246,000) is substantial. At a typical
        <a href="/valuation/landscaping-yard-services/">landscaping industry multiple of 2.76× SDE</a>,
        the SDE-based valuation is approximately $678,000. If a buyer or advisor applied a mid-market
        EBITDA multiple of 5.0× instead, they would get $560,000 on the EBITDA — significantly lower
        despite the "higher" multiple. SDE captures more earnings and applies to this business;
        EBITDA does not.
      </p>

      <h2>The Decision Framework: Which Metric Applies to Your Business</h2>

      <div class="data-table-wrap">
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th scope="col">Factor</th>
              <th scope="col">Use SDE</th>
              <th scope="col">Use EBITDA</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Revenue</td>
              <td>Under $5M</td>
              <td>$5M+</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Earnings</td>
              <td>Under $1M SDE</td>
              <td>$1M+ EBITDA</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Management</td>
              <td>Owner-operated</td>
              <td>Professional management team</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Buyer type</td>
              <td>Individual operator, SBA buyer</td>
              <td>PE firm, strategic acquirer</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Owner role</td>
              <td>Daily operator</td>
              <td>Capital allocator, board-level</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h2>The Multiple Difference: SDE vs. EBITDA</h2>
      <p>
        EBITDA multiples for Main Street businesses are not higher than SDE multiples — they are
        applied to a smaller earnings base. The multiple differences:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Main Street SDE multiples: typically 2.0× – 5.0× (varies significantly by industry)</li>
        <li>Lower middle market EBITDA multiples: typically 4.0× – 7.0× ($1M–$5M EBITDA)</li>
        <li>Mid-market EBITDA multiples: typically 6.0× – 12.0× ($5M+ EBITDA)</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        A business crossing from Main Street into lower middle market — say, $1.2M SDE — may actually
        benefit from being positioned on an EBITDA basis if it has professional management that would
        continue post-sale, because the 5–7× EBITDA multiples applied to a smaller number may exceed
        the 3–4× SDE multiple applied to the larger number. This is a calculation that requires a
        sophisticated broker to navigate — the right metric is a deal-structuring decision, not just
        an accounting choice.
      </p>

      <h2>When Sellers Use the Wrong Metric</h2>
      <p>
        The most common mistake: a Main Street seller reads about EBITDA multiples in financial media
        (where mid-market multiples of 8–12× are reported) and expects those multiples to apply to
        their $400,000 SDE landscaping business. They do not. Those multiples apply to different-sized
        businesses with professional management and different risk profiles.
      </p>
      <p>
        The correct approach: use the industry-specific SDE multiple from real transaction data for
        your business type and size. The <a href="/">valuation calculator</a> uses
        SDE multiples derived from {{ site.transactionCount }}+ closed Main Street transactions.
        If your business is above the $5M revenue threshold, consult a business broker or M&amp;A
        advisor about whether EBITDA positioning makes sense.
      </p>

      <h2>Seller's Discretionary Earnings in Practice</h2>
      <p>
        Most business owners start by using SDE — the right choice for the vast majority of small
        business sales. The practical workflow:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>Calculate your SDE using the method in the <a href="/guides/what-is-sde/">SDE guide</a></li>
        <li>Enter your SDE in the <a href="/">valuation calculator</a> with your industry, revenue, and adjustment factors</li>
        <li>Use the resulting range as your baseline for pricing discussions with your broker</li>
        <li>If your SDE is above $1M, ask your broker whether EBITDA positioning might apply</li>
      </ol>

